<dl id="n17061e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n17" href="#n17061e">N17 (VI.B.9)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n17all.htm#n17061e"> 61(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Swithin Winchester/ 15 &frasl; 7 / christening the apples / S. Medard <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n17061e"><li>FW 433.35 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n17061e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n17061e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n17061e">MS BL 47483-113</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:179 <a name="qAd5" href="../../FF/fdra/qda.htm#qAd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/qA/qAd5.htm#n17061e">Draft: III&sect;2A.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">THE RAINY SAINT &hellip; History tells us that <mark>Swithin was born in the neighbourhood of Winchester</mark> about the year 800 &hellip;. From this account <font color="green">[of a ceremony to erect a chapel over his grave]</font> &hellip; the still current belief arose that a wet St. Swithin&apos;s Day will surely prophesy forty subsequent days of rain &hellip;. The fallacy of this has been proved many times by observations at Greenwich, yet the belief has persisted, and most of us are secretly relieved when there is no rain on <mark>the 15th of July,</mark> and when St. Swithin refrains from <mark>&ldquo;christening the apples&rdquo;.</mark> Other countries have their rainy saints, such as St. Godelieve of Belgium and the French <mark>St. M&eacute;dard,</mark> whose day falls upon the 8th of June, that one hot summer day he went with a number of people, when a sudden downpour of rain drenched the whole party, with the exception of the saint himself. <small> <a name="IT6jul25" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#IT6jul25"><cite title="source">Irish Times</cite></a> (6 July 1925) 3/3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: &lsquo;Swithin Winchester 15&frasl;7&rsquo; is not crossed through. </mm> </dd></dl>
